<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="21">
[[ Genus 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5D5C78EA-1E5B-4C98-8CB2-677B409FBBD2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Epalzeorhynchos Bleeker 1855:258, 270" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Epalzeorhynchos Bleeker</taxonomicName>
]]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="21">
The Labeoninae (sensu Chen et al., 1984), which is essentially equivalent to the Labeines of Reid (1982) or the tribe Labeone (= Labeonini) of Rainboth (1991, 1996), includes cyprinid fishes widely distributed in the fresh waters of tropical Africa and Asia. Most of these fishes are adapted to fast flowing waters. Members of this subfamily show a high degree of morphological modification in oromandibular structures, which is the basis for recognition of most of its included genera. To date, twenty-seven Labeonine genera have been recognized from eastern and southeastern Asia (Rainboth, 1991; Zhang &amp; Chen, 2004). Among these, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5D5C78EA-1E5B-4C98-8CB2-677B409FBBD2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Epalzeorhynchos Bleeker 1855:258, 270" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Epalzeorhynchos Bleeker, 1855</taxonomicName>
(type species: 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:FD3B3440-09A1-40A3-8CA0-1A2A72BB9BC9" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Barbus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Barbus kalopterus Bleeker 1851:13" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kalopterus">Barbus kalopterus Bleeker, 1851</taxonomicName>
) is diagnosed by having a pair of moveable lateral lobes on the snout, which are also called “fleshy rostral papilla” (Roberts, 1989) or “posteriorly free lateral lobes” (Yang &amp; Winterbottom, 1998). Five valid species have so far been identified in 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5D5C78EA-1E5B-4C98-8CB2-677B409FBBD2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Epalzeorhynchos Bleeker 1855:258, 270" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Epalzeorhynchos</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bicolor">E. bicolor</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bicornis">E. bicornis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="frenatus">E. frenatus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kalopterus">E. kalopterus</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="munensis">E. munensis</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bicornis">Epalzeorhynchos bicornis</taxonomicName>
was described by Wu et al. (1977), based on a single 140 mm SL specimen from the upper Salween River (= Nu Jiang in Chinese) basin in Liuku County, Yunnan Province, China. Although 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bicornis">E. bicornis</taxonomicName>
is currently regarded as valid (Chu &amp; Cui, 1989; Chen, 1998; Zhang et al., 2000), its generic position is still unclear. Kottelat (1989) commented that 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bicornis">E. bicornis</taxonomicName>
does not belong in 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5D5C78EA-1E5B-4C98-8CB2-677B409FBBD2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Epalzeorhynchos Bleeker 1855:258, 270" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Epalzeorhynchos</taxonomicName>
, but did not elaborate further. Yang and Winterbottom (1998) investigated the relationships among the five currently identified species of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5D5C78EA-1E5B-4C98-8CB2-677B409FBBD2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Epalzeorhynchos Bleeker 1855:258, 270" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Epalzeorhynchos</taxonomicName>
. They demonstrated that 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bicornis">E. bicornis</taxonomicName>
is sister to 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F425B29-C4AC-46B4-8125-D8C710AD8BB9" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Paracrossochilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Paracrossochilus Popta 1904:200" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Paracrossochilus</taxonomicName>
when 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Crossocheilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Crossocheilus</taxonomicName>
is used as the outgroup, and that it is basal to the clade that includes 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Crossocheilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Crossocheilus</taxonomicName>
and other species of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5D5C78EA-1E5B-4C98-8CB2-677B409FBBD2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Epalzeorhynchos Bleeker 1855:258, 270" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Epalzeorhynchos</taxonomicName>
, when 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F425B29-C4AC-46B4-8125-D8C710AD8BB9" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Paracrossochilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Paracrossochilus Popta 1904:200" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Paracrossochilus</taxonomicName>
is utilized as the outgroup. These findings led Yang and Winterbottom to conclude that 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bicornis">E. bicornis</taxonomicName>
should not be placed in 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5D5C78EA-1E5B-4C98-8CB2-677B409FBBD2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Epalzeorhynchos Bleeker 1855:258, 270" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Epalzeorhynchos</taxonomicName>
, but they stopped short of erecting a new genus for its reception.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="22">
Kottelat’s (1989) and Yang and Winterbottom’s (1998) observation that 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bicornis">E. bicornis</taxonomicName>
is not immediately associated with the other species of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5D5C78EA-1E5B-4C98-8CB2-677B409FBBD2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Epalzeorhynchos Bleeker 1855:258, 270" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Epalzeorhynchos</taxonomicName>
is corroborated by marked differences we found in position and structure of the moveable lateral lobes on the snout and the morphology of the oromandibular structures. Morphology of the oromandibular structures is diagnostic for many Labeoninae genera (Zhang et al., 2000; Zhang &amp; Chen, 2004), and the differences we observed among species of 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5D5C78EA-1E5B-4C98-8CB2-677B409FBBD2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Epalzeorhynchos Bleeker 1855:258, 270" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Epalzeorhynchos</taxonomicName>
indicate that 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Cyprinidae" genus="Epalzeorhynchos" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cypriniformes" pageNumber="22" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bicornis">E. bicornis</taxonomicName>
belongs to a distinct genus, which we describe and name in the present paper.
</paragraph>
